article.description: Diana Taurasi scored 27 of her 31 points in the first half and led top-ranked Connecticut to an 81-53 victory Tuesday night over Florida State.
article.headline: Taurasi scores 31 points in rout

images.name: Taurasi_Diana 031125 inline
images.caption: Without her fouls, the sky was the limit Tuesday for Taurasi.

article.linkText: No. 1 UConn rolls over Florida State
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Florida State was rolling right along,
draining just about everything against top-ranked Connecticut in
the first half.

<photo1>The Seminoles shot 67 percent in the first 12 minutes, but it
still wasn't enough to trip up Diana Taurasi. The UConn star scored
27 of her 31 points in the first half, and the Huskies pulled away
for an 81-53 victory Tuesday night.

"Gosh, what didn't she do?" Florida State coach Sue Semrau
asked. "We put our two best defenders on her and she just did a
tremendous job."

Taurasi's 27 points was a personal best for half. She poured in
12 points during a 22-7 run in the final 7:50 of the first half,
allowing the Huskies (2-0) to turn a tie game into a 50-35 halftime
advantage.

The Seminoles opened two days ago with one of the most lopsided
victories in NCAA history, holding Savannah State to three
first-half points in 107-28 rout. They've gone from playing one of
the worst teams to one of the best.

"They're the toughest team that I've seen in my years of
coaching," Semrau said. "If things don't go their way, there's a
confidence about them. When they made their little run at the end
of the first half, they were doing what they do best."

Taurasi, last year's national player of the year, has scored at
least 20 points in the last eight games dating back to the NCAA
tournament.

"The last couple of days, I've been shooting the ball pretty
well and when that happens you play carefree and you've got a lot
of confidence," Taurasi said.

Foul trouble kept Taurasi on the bench for long stretches in the
second half. She finished 9-of-13 from the field, including 5-of-7
from behind the arc. With six assists, she was involved in 17 of
UConn's 25 field goals.

Besides trying to handle the defending national champions,
Florida State had problems with free throws, too, making just
9-of-19. UConn was 22 of 29 from the line.

Florida State managed just 18 points in the second half.

Barbara Turner added 15 points for UConn, and Jessica Moore led
the Huskies inside with nine rebounds. Reserve forward Morgan
Valley grabbed eight boards and had three steals in 16 minutes for
UConn.

The Huskies finished with 11 steals and nine blocks, and scored
20 points off turnovers.

Tasheika Allen led the Seminoles with 21 points and teammate
Genesis Choice grabbed nine rebounds.

Taurasi's first-half performance even took her coach by
surprise.

"I didn't realize it until I got into the locker room what she
had done," UConn coach Geno Auriemma said. "I knew she had played
well, obviously, but I didn't know she had 27 points.

"She had a little different look in her eye before the game.
She just makes it look so easy."
